{"type":"message","id":"22005e2c","parentId":"cffa7498","timestamp":"2026-04-09T00:53:07.281Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The write access is confirmed as True. The script logic looks straightforward - just writes a CSV. But the log shows `Operation not permitted` failures.\n\nWait, let me re-read the log output more carefully. The last entry in the sector_sync.log was from April 7 (yesterday before the holiday). Today is April 9. Let me check if there's any entry for April 8 or today in the log.Actually wait - looking at the timestamp again: `[09:20:01] 开始同步行业板块数据...` - this is from April 7 pre-holiday. After that, the market was closed April 4-6 (Qingming). \n\nSo today is April 9 and the market is open, but the sector_sync.log only has entries through April 7 - nothing for April 8 or today. The cron job clearly ran based on the log entries, but it stopped executing after April 7, which suggests either the cron job itself isn't running anymore or there's something preventing it from executing on the subsequent days.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the \"Operation not permitted\" error is coming from the **script trying to write to the industries.csv file**, not from the cron execution itself. The cron is running fine, but the script doesn't have permission to write its output file. But when I tested writing to that same path, it worked fine - so either the script is being run as a different user through cron, or there's something else going on with how the symlink resolves permissions.\n\nLet me check if there's maybe an immutable flag or file lock on the CSV that's preventing the script from modifying it, even though my direct write test worked.","thinkingSignature":"3a5ef4d4022b3cae0e70fdb67e1a8a50958dd574ea2731d92f9290dbdb4ee739"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_e6umoy0lohg2_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check if there's file locking or immutable flag\npython3 -c \"\nimport os, stat\np = '/Volumes/A/op