{"type":"message","id":"ec17c434","parentId":"80e65ae2","timestamp":"2026-04-09T00:53:57.764Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `sector_heatmap_summary.json` was last updated on April 8 at 18:22 - that's after the market closed (15:00) on April 8, the first trading day after Qingming. So the data IS being updated. The `sync_sector_board_data.py` IS successfully updating the JSON file, but fails on the CSV.\n\nBut wait - the `sector_heatmap_summary.json` was updated at 18:22 on April 8, which means the script DID run after the market closed on April 8. But the `industries.csv` is still dated April 7 - meaning the CSV write consistently fails.\n\n\nSo the JSON is being written successfully but the CSV isn't. Looking at the save functions, the JSON summary gets written to `research/reports/` which has write permissions, while the CSV tries to go to `data/` where the write fails. The cron job ran on April 8 at 18:22, successfully wrote the JSON, but couldn't update the CSV.\n\nThe `[新鲜]` tag in market_pulse comes from `get_sector_breadth()` reading the `sector_heatmap_summary.json`, not the stale `industries.csv`. So the dashboard data freshness depends on the JSON's `generated_at` timestamp - if it was written today, it would show fresh, even though the underlying CSV data is old.\n\nNow I'm realizing the actual issue is that industries.csv is stale (April 7), and any downstream processes that depend on it would be working with outdated data. But sector_heatmap_summary.json was updated today. The \"Operation not permitted\" error on industries.csv is the real problem - the data was fetched successfully but can't be persisted, so the cron job is running but the data isn't being saved properly. Let me look at what's actually triggering that permission error.\n\nLooking at the code path: `save_csv()` is being called, which means industries.csv is where the write fails. The permissions check shows `staff` group has no read/write access, only the owner does - and on macOS, root is typically not a member of the `staff` group, so even though cron runs as root, it can't write to a file owned by `ling` with 0x600 permissions. But wait, cron jobs run as the crontab owner, not as root, so the real issue is that the file is owned by `ling` with 0o600 permissions and I'm not sure if cron is actually running as `ling` or root.\n\nLooking at the log output from the system, the sector_sync.log entries with timestamps like `[09:20:01]` are being generated by the cron job, which suggests the cron is executing. I need to check the process list more carefully to see what user the python3 processes are actually running as.","thinkingSignature":"b19b01c6f507a4afbe5adb0b7534c4faedbb100ab05bb9b41dc5e617eeaa206a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ikwjhj8lnxwn_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check what user the cron jobs are running as\nps aux | grep -E \"python3|sync\" | grep -v grep | head -10"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ikwjhj8lnxwn_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check the research reports directory permissions - that's where the JSON is written\nls -la /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/ 2>/dev/null | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":13116,"output":699,"cacheRead":19969,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":33784,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775696017622,"responseId":"06262b935ea2156f181bef8227eae9ec"}}
