{"type":"message","id":"14b0f7f9","parentId":"0ffffc51","timestamp":"2026-04-09T00:55:09.808Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait! The `sector_sync.log` was last modified at `Apr 8 15:30` - that's AFTER the market closed on April 8 (market closes at 15:00). So the cron DID run on April 8! But the log file only has 84 lines, and the last entries I saw were from April 7...\n\nOh wait - the log shows `[09:20:01] 开始同步行业板块数据...` which could be from April 8 or April 7. The sector_sync.log file was modified at 15:30 on April 8, so the script DID run on April 8. But the content seems to not show April 8 entries. \n\nI'm getting confused by the timestamps here - the market closes at 15:00 on April 8, so a 15:30 cron job should have run, but looking at the actual log content from the `tail -50` output, those entries don't show any April 8 markers. Let me check the log file modification time again to figure out what's actually happening.\n\nThe `sector_heatmap_summary.json` file shows it was updated at `Apr 8 18:22`, which is after the market closed, so that cron job definitely executed. But if the last sector_sync.log entry shows `Apr 8 15:30` and the json was created at 18:22, either the json was updated by a different process or I'm looking at the wrong log file. Let me trace through what actually ran on April 8 versus what the logs are showing me.\n\nThe issue might be with how the data file permissions are set up - the directory is owned by `staff` group but has `drwx------` permissions, which could be blocking write access even though the cron job should be running as the correct user. Let me just test the most direct fix: manually updating the industries.csv file to see if that resolves the sync issue, then investigate the permission problem separately.\n\nNow I'm realizing the core tension here - the user expects automatic daily updates, but the write permissions keep failing and the industries.csv file stays stale. The sector_heatmap_summary.json gets generated instead, which might be feeding the dashboard, but I need to verify whether that's actually working or just masking the underlying problem. I need to dig into why the JSON write succeeded on April 8 at 18:22 while the CSV write failed with a permission error, since they should be writing to the same symlinked directory with the same ownership. The ownership might be different, or there's something else going on with how the file system is handling the two writes. I'm wondering if the issue is related to how macOS handles file creation through symlinks, particularly with AFP or network drives. But I should stop speculating and just try the straightforward approach: manually write to the CSV file to confirm it works, then handle the underlying issue separately. The real question is whether the dashboard data is actually current or if there's a deeper problem with how the sector_heatmap_summary.json is being read.\n\nLet me look at what the market_pulse.py is actually checking for freshness.","thinkingSignature":"e962a3ea8abdeb7991d808e55018c1824e4061da13f5a7a77c7003f90978cca5"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0irb9c0j9818_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check when the dashboard was last rendered and with what data\ncat /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/sector_heatmap_summary.json 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":17170,"output":709,"cacheRead":19969,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":37848,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775696088802,"responseId":"06262bdadf14f48faf8565729a6fb150"}}
