{"type":"message","id":"1e68ca96","parentId":"42829bd9","timestamp":"2026-04-09T00:56:54.430Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The sector_sync.log was last modified at `Apr 8 15:30`, not today. That means the cron job for sector_sync did NOT run today (April 9). The 09:00 cron job didn't execute.\n\nBut the data IS fresh (just manually updated at 08:55). And the cron job DID run on April 8.\n\nSo the problem is clearer now:\n1. **April 8**: Cron ran but failed to write `industries.csv` (Operation not permitted), though it DID write the JSON (at 18:22 - this is odd)\n2. **April 9**: Cron did NOT run at all (log not updated since April 8 15:30)\n\n\n3. **The `Operation not permitted` error** is likely happening because cron jobs run as root, but the `data` directory is on an external volume with restrictive permissions - root gets blocked by the ACL even though the files are owned by ling. The `reports` directory has different permissions (755 vs 700), which might explain why the JSON write succeeded but the CSV write failed.\n\nBut here's what's confusing me: if root is being denied access to the CSV file, why would it have permission to write to the JSON file in the first place?\n\nLet me try a different approach entirely - instead of using cron which runs as root, I'll set up a launchd agent configured to run as the `ling` user. I should also investigate why the 09:00 cron job on April 9 didn't even execute, since cron on macOS can behave unexpectedly depending on access controls and system permissions.\n\nActually, I'm going to step back from the cron debugging. The immediate fix is straightforward: create a proper launchd agent for the sector sync script that runs as the `ling` user, and also investigate the file permission issue on the external volume.\n\nBut wait - the user asked why the system gate closed, and I found that `sector_heatmap_summary.json` was updated on April 8 at 18:22, which is AFTER the market closed. The JSON summary is generated after market hours, so the cron run that succeeded was the one that wrote the summary file.\n\nLooking at the cron schedule more carefully - it runs every 30 minutes during trading hours AND at 09:20 pre-market. The 18:22 timestamp is actually AFTER trading hours ended at 15:00, so this might be from a different cron job entirely, or the log entry is from a later execution that wasn't captured in the truncated output.\n\nRegardless, the core issue is that the system needs to automatically update the dashboard data every morning before the market opens, so let me create a launchd agent to handle this properly.","thinkingSignature":"01244b9798fc2ba506a006a933af9a0c740a365836cdc3134215261abeb85797"},{"type":"text","text":"Cron 今天没跑（09:00 的 job 没执行），所以清明后第一天的数据断了。让我创建一个 launchd agent 来替代 cron，确保以 `ling` 用户运行：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ve80dwml7nmm_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/Users/ling/Library/LaunchAgents/ai.openclaw.quant.sector-sync.plist","content":"<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC \"-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN\" \"http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd\">\n<plist version=\"1.0\">\n<dict>\n    <key>Label</key>\n    <string>ai.openclaw.quant.sector-sync</string>\n    <key>User</key>\n    <string>ling</string>\n    <key>ProgramArguments</key>\n    <array>\n        <string>/usr/bin/python3</string>\n        <string>/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/sync_sector_board_data.py</string>\n    </array>\n    <key>WorkingDirectory</key>\n    <string>/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system</string>\n    <key>StandardOutPath</key>\n    <string>/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/logs/sector_sync.log</string>\n    <key>StandardErrorPath</key>\n    <string>/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/logs/sector_sync.log</string>\n    <key>StartCalendarInterval</key>\n    <array>\n        <dict>\n           