{"type":"message","id":"4446b5bf","parentId":"7df2b351","timestamp":"2026-04-09T01:19:39.572Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so there's no pre-built llama-cli or llama-server. The llama.cpp source is there but not built. And Ollama is installed separately (its own binary with its own model storage).\n\nLet me think about this differently. The user wants to:1. Remove Ollama models (free up ~17GB)\n2. Install more local models via \"oMLX\"\n\nGiven the context:- Ollama uses its own binary and model format (not GGUF)\n- oMLX was configured to run on port 8000 with specific models\n- The llama.cpp source is available but not built\n\nI think \"oMLX\" in this context is a llama.cpp server running GGUF models. The models were served from port 8000 (which is currently down).\n\n\nI need to clarify whether the user wants to build a llama.cpp server with Metal support for GGUF models, or if they're looking for a specific MLX-format setup for Apple Silicon. Let me ask them directly what they want to accomplish with oMLX and which models they're interested in, rather than continuing to guess at the setup. Looking at the disk space, I've got about 64GB available, which is more than enough to work with. The core issue is that Ollama and oMLX are independent systems—Ollama has its own models and binary, while oMLX needs a llama.cpp server with MLX support. I should walk through what models the user is currently running via Ollama, explain what it would mean to migrate to oMLX, and then let them decide which direction makes sense based on their goals.","thinkingSignature":"f02ed4088ca9713e7bd81d88efe52d807a45f36dd669b76d1c871ab687a3ea21"},{"type":"text","text":"\n情况先理清楚：\n\n**当前 Ollama 里装的是：**\n| 模型 | 大小 |\n|------|------|\n| `omnicoder-9b` | 5.7 GB |\n| `my-qwen:latest` | 5.7 GB |\n| `deepseek-r1:7b` | 4.7 GB |\n| `bge-m3`（嵌入模型） | 1.2 GB |\n| **合计** | **~17.3 GB** |\n\n**oMLX**（端口 8000）现在没在运行，之前只配了 2 个极小模型（0.5B 和 1.5B）。\n\n把 oMLX 跑起来需要